The number of electrons in the conduction band, whose bottom is $
\varepsilon_{\mathrm{C}}$, and the number of holes in the valence band, whose top is $
\varepsilon_{\mathrm{V}}$, are respectively
\[
 egin{array}{l}
n=\int_{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{C}}}^{\infty} N(E) f(E) d E \np=\int_{-\infty}^{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{V}}} N(E)(1-f(E)) d E
\end{array}
\]
where
\[
f(E)= rac{1}{e^{\left(E-E_{\mathrm{F}}ight) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}+1}
\]
is the Fermi-Dirac distribution function giving the probability that an energy level $E$ is occupied. For an intrinsic semiconductor, $n=p$, from which the Fermi level $E_{\mathrm{F}}$ can be derived. For example consider the case where $E-E_{\mathrm{F}} \gg k_{\mathrm{B}} T$, then $f(E) \approx e^{-\left(E-E_{\mathrm{F}}ight) k_{\mathrm{B}} T}$, whence
\[
 egin{array}{l}
n \approx \int_{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{C}}}^{\infty} n_{0} e^{-\left(E-E_{\mathrm{F}}ight) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T} d E=n_{0} k_{\mathrm{B}} T e^{-\left(\varepsilon_{\mathrm{C}}-E_{\mathrm{F}}ight) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}, \np \approx n_{0} k_{\mathrm{B}} T e^{-\left(E_{\mathrm{F}}-\varepsilon_{\mathrm{V}}ight) / k_{\mathrm{B}} T}
\end{array}
\]
where $n_{0}$ is the density of electron states. From $n=p$ we have
\[
E_{\mathrm{F}}= rac{\varepsilon_{\mathrm{C}}+\varepsilon_{\mathrm{V}}}{2}
\]

